a-backdrop=\"static\" data-return-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2528617\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 12, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104imu1665702870948.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/imu1665702870948.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/imu1665702870948.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"imu1665702870948\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n                  \n Selecting and Sorting Data for Printing \n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body refbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Selecting and sorting your data before printing is critical to good reports. If it is not feasible to select and sort your data before printing, you can also manipulate occurrences during printing, although this is less efficient.\n </p>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"imu1665702870948__section_w617ab1b5b1_w618ab1b5_w619ab1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d1056815e51\">\n                    \n Selecting Data\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25169e1_d25170e1_d25171e1\">The component data structure provides the initial data selection, but further selection criteria are required to retrieve, for example, all employees with a certain salary or higher. In a form component, the user can enter a retrieve profile to select the data. In a report component, the selection criteria must be provided using ProcScript.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25172e1_d25173e1_d25174e1\">Use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">u_where</span> clause with the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">read</span> statement in the read trigger of the entity concerned, specifying the retrieve profile you require. For example:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">trigger read ; of entity INVOICE\n read u_where (INVAMOUNT &gt; 500) order by \"INVAMOUNT\"\nend; read</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"imu1665702870948__section_w620ab1b5b3_w621ab1b5_w622ab1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d1056815e72\">\n                    \n Sorting Data\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25178e1_d25179e1_d25180e1\">Data sorting plays an important role in the purpose of a report. For example, a report about unpaid invoices which are sorted by date has a different purpose to one in which the invoices are sorted by amount.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25181e1_d25182e1_d25183e1\">When the data in your report does not come from the database in the required order, use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">order by</span> clause with the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">read</span> statement in the read trigger of the entity concerned, specifying the field or fields you want to sort by. Alternatively, use the <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">sort</span> statement.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25184e1_d25185e1_d25186e1\">Below is an example of the order by clause in ProcScript in the read trigger:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">trigger read ; of entity INVOICE\n read order by \"INVAMOUNT\"\nend; read</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"imu1665702870948__note_w623ab1b5b3c11_w624ab1b5b3_w625ab1b5_w626ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> Ascending and descending sorting is not always possible with the\n                                        <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">order by</span> clause for all DBMSs. See the\n                                appropriate DBMS connector documentation about your DBMS.</div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"imu1665702870948__p_d25187e1_d25188e1_d25189e1\">If your data is already in the correct order when it reaches Uniface, do not use an <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">order by</span> clause. This is an unnecessary use of resources which slows the procedure down considerably.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/hcs1665703005814.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>read</a><p>Fetch an occurrence from the hitlist.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/grx1665703129707.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>trigger read</a><p>System trigger that fetches an occurrence from the database.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528617\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528617\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Selecting and Sorting Data for Printing Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 12, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Selecting and Sorting Data for Printing Selecting and sorting your data before printing is critical to good reports. If it is not feasible to select and sort your data before printing, you can also manipulate occurrences during printing, although this is less efficient. Selecting Data The component data structure provides the initial data selection, but further selection criteria are required to retrieve, for example, all employees with a certain salary or higher. In a form component, the user can enter a retrieve profile to select the data. In a report component, the selection criteria must be provided using ProcScript. Use the u_where clause with the read statement in the read trigger of the entity concerned, specifying the retrieve profile you require. For example: trigger read ; of entity INVOICE read u_where (INVAMOUNT > 500) order by \"INVAMOUNT\" end; read Copy Sorting Data Data sorting plays an important role in the purpose of a report. For example, a report about unpaid invoices which are sorted by date has a different purpose to one in which the invoices are sorted by amount. When the data in your report does not come from the database in the required order, use the order by clause with the read statement in the read trigger of the entity concerned, specifying the field or fields you want to sort by. Alternatively, use the sort statement. Below is an example of the order by clause in ProcScript in the read trigger: trigger read ; of entity INVOICE read order by \"INVAMOUNT\" end; read Copy Note: Ascending and descending sorting is not always possible with the order by clause for all DBMSs. See the appropriate DBMS connector documentation about your DBMS. If your data is already in the correct order when it reaches Uniface, do not use an order by clause. This is an unnecessary use of resources which slows the procedure down considerably. Related Links read Fetch an occurrence from the hitlist. trigger read System trigger that fetches an occurrence from the database. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}